<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1929-09-03T02:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1929-09-03T02:00:00-05:00" n="210" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d210">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">861.77 Chinese Eastern/299:
                            Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">MacMurray</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1929-09-03T15:00:00+08:00">September 3, 1929—3
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received 11:23 p.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>788. My 781, September 1, 11 a.m. Following from American Consul at
                            Harbin: <quote rend="blockquote">
                                <p>“Sept. 3, 10 a.m. American correspondents Powell, Wright, Goette,
                                    now at Manchuria Station, have reported to their respective
                                    newspapers that regular Soviet troops have invaded and have
                                    taken up positions inside Chinese territory and have shelled
                                    Chinese outposts. However they have taken the word of the
                                    Chinese authorities as to where the boundary is.”</p>
                            </quote></p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">MacMurray</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>